# C++ Coding Standards

## 1. Code Style
- Follow **Google C++ Style Guide** strictly
- Use **C++23** features and modern practices
- **No `using` directives in header files** - use fully qualified names
- Use `using` aliases in `.cc` files for long type names (e.g., `using Status = absl::Status`)

## 2. Error Handling
- Use `absl::Status` and `absl::StatusOr<T>` for error handling (via project wrappers)
- Use `CHECK` and `CHECK_OK` macros for assertions
- Use `RETURN_IF_ERROR` and `RETURN_ERROR_IF` macros from [txm/base/status/status.h](mdc:txm/base/status/status.h)
- **When using status functionality**: `#include "txm/base/status/status.h"` instead of `#include "absl/status/status.h"`

## 3. Logging
- Use logging macros from [txm/base/cpp/log/log.h](mdc:txm/base/cpp/log/log.h) for all log output
- Use `LOG(INFO)`, `LOG(WARNING)`, `LOG(ERROR)`, `LOG(FATAL)` macros instead of `absl::log::Log`
- Include necessary logging headers: `#include "txm/base/cpp/log/log.h"`

## 4. Headers and Includes
- Use `#pragma once` for header guards [TXM] *(overrides [GSG#The__define_Guard])*
- Include order *(enforced by clang-format)*: corresponding `.h` first (e.g., `foo.cc` includes `foo.h` first) → C system headers (`<*.h>`) → C++ standard library (`<vector>`) → project headers (`"txm/..."`) → third-party [TXM] *(differs from [GSG#Names_and_Order_of_Includes])*
- Use C++17 nested namespace syntax: `namespace a::b::c` instead of `namespace a { namespace b { namespace c {`
- Avoid using forward declarations where possible. Instead, include the headers you need. [GSG#Forward_Declarations]
- Include what you use: directly include headers for all symbols you use, don't rely on transitive includes. [GSG#Include_What_You_Use]
- **MANDATORY**: When modifying `#include` statements for `"txm/..."` or third-party headers, update BUILD file's `deps` accordingly: add missing deps, remove unused deps [TXM]

## 5. Naming Conventions
- Classes: `PascalCase` (e.g., `ComponentBase`)
- Functions: `PascalCase` (e.g., `ProcessInternal`, `GetUserData`)
- Variables: `snake_case` (e.g., `user_data`, `max_retries`)
- Constants: `kConstantName` (e.g., `kMaxRetries`)
- Private members: `member_name_` (trailing underscore)
- Namespaces: `snake_case`, top-level based on project name (e.g., `txm::base::image`) [GSG#Namespace_Names]
- Enumerators: `kEnumValue` (like constants), not `MACRO_STYLE` [GSG#Enumerator_Names]

## 6. Modern C++ Features
- **Ownership**: Prefer `std::unique_ptr` (exclusive); use `std::shared_ptr` only when ownership is truly shared [GSG#Ownership_and_Smart_Pointers]
- **Raw pointers mean "not owned"** - never use raw pointers to transfer ownership; use `std::move` with smart pointers
- Prefer `auto` for type deduction when type is obvious
- Use concepts for template constraints (C++20)
- Use `std::optional` for optional values
- Use range-based for loops and algorithms

## 7. Class Design and Inheritance [GSG#Classes]
- **REQUIRED**: Use `explicit` for single-argument constructors (prevents implicit conversions) [GSG#Implicit_Conversions]
- **REQUIRED**: Base classes must have virtual destructors
- **REQUIRED**: Non-polymorphic classes must be marked `final`
- **REQUIRED**: Use `override` for virtual function overrides (enables compiler checking) [GSG#Inheritance]
- Use `DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN` or `DISALLOW_COPY_AND_MOVE` macros from [txm/base/cpp/macros.h](mdc:txm/base/cpp/macros.h) instead of manually writing `= delete`
- Use `struct` for passive data bundles; `class` for objects with invariants or behavior [GSG#Structs_vs._Classes]

## 8. absl::Flag Usage
- Use `absl::Flag` for command-line flags and configuration parameters
- Include necessary flag headers:  `#include "txm/base/cpp/flag/flag.h"`
- **Flag declaration pattern**:
  ```cpp
  ABSL_FLAG(std::string, config_file, "default.conf", "Path to configuration file");
  ABSL_FLAG(int32_t, max_retries, 3, "Maximum number of retry attempts");
  ABSL_FLAG(bool, enable_debug, false, "Enable debug logging");
  ```
- **Flag access pattern**:
  ```cpp
  std::string config_path = absl::GetFlag(FLAGS_config_file);
  int32_t retries = absl::GetFlag(FLAGS_max_retries);
  bool debug_enabled = absl::GetFlag(FLAGS_enable_debug);
  ```
- **Main function pattern**:
  ```cpp
  int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    absl::ParseCommandLine(argc, argv);
    // ... rest of main logic
  }
  ```
- **Flag naming**: Use `snake_case` for flag names (e.g., `config_file`, `max_retries`)
- **Default values**: Always provide meaningful defaults
- **Help text**: Write clear, concise descriptions for each flag
- **Type safety**: Use appropriate types (`std::string`, `int32_t`, `bool`, `double`, etc.)

## 9. Comments
- Use `//` for single-line comments, `/* */` for multi-line
- **Use concise function comments without @brief, @param, @return tags**
- Example: `// Push element to queue (blocking version)` instead of `/** @brief Push element... */`
- **Comment only necessary code, not obvious implementations**
- **DO NOT comment obvious code**: function names, simple assignments, basic control flow
- **DO comment**: non-obvious business logic, complex algorithms, edge cases, performance considerations
- **Bad examples**: `// Push element to queue`, `// Add to back`, `// Check if empty`
- **Good examples**: `// If queue is full, overwrite oldest element`, `// Handle edge case when buffer wraps around`

## 10. Parameter Comments (Minimalism Principle)
- **Core principle**: Variable names should be self-documenting; comments should only add information the name cannot convey
- **DELETE @param if**: The comment merely restates or paraphrases the parameter name
- **KEEP @param if**: The comment provides essential context that cannot be expressed in the name:
  - Units of measurement (e.g., `// in milliseconds`, `// bytes per row`)
  - Valid value ranges (e.g., `// 0-255`, `// must be power of 2`)
  - Memory layout details (e.g., `// row-major`, `// transposed`)
  - Pre/post-conditions (e.g., `// must be pre-allocated`, `// caller owns memory`)
  - Special semantics (e.g., `// nullptr means use default`)

### Decision Checklist
Before writing a @param comment, ask:
1. Does the parameter name already convey this information?
2. Can I improve the parameter name instead of adding a comment?
3. Is this information essential for correct usage?
If answers are "yes, no, no" → DELETE the comment

## 11. Control Flow

### Always Use Braces [TXM]
**Always** enclose control statement bodies with braces, even for single statements.
*(GSG allows exceptions for historical reasons; we do not allow them)*

```cpp
// GOOD
if (condition) {
  return false;
}

// BAD - no braces (GSG exception, but NOT allowed here)
if (x == kFoo) return new Foo();

// BAD - same line with braces (GSG exception, but NOT allowed here)
if (x == kFoo) { return new Foo(); }

// BAD - condition and body on separate lines without braces
if (x == kBar)
  Bar(arg1, arg2, arg3);
```

### Use Early Return/Continue
Prefer early return/continue to reduce nesting and improve readability.

## 12. Function Parameters [GSG#Functions]

### Parameter Rules
- **Prefer return values** over output parameters for returning data
- **Parameter order**: inputs first, outputs last
- **Input parameters**: value or `const&`; optional inputs use `const T*`
- **Output parameters**: non-optional use `T&`; optional use `T*`
- **Virtual functions**: never use default arguments (binds at compile-time, not polymorphic)

```cpp
// GOOD - return value preferred
Config LoadConfig();

// GOOD - non-optional output via reference
absl::Status LoadConfig(const std::string& path, Config& out_config);

// GOOD - optional output via pointer
absl::Status TryLoadConfig(const std::string& path, Config* out_config);

// GOOD - optional input via const pointer
void Process(const Config* optional_config = nullptr);
```

## 13. Map Variable Naming
Use `{key}_to_{value}` pattern for map variables:
```cpp
// GOOD
std::map<std::string, LogData> module_name_to_log_data_;

// BAD
std::map<std::string, LogData> log_data_map_;
```

## 14. Include Order
Use `""` for project headers (not `<>`), so clang-format sorts them correctly after system headers:
```cpp
// GOOD - clang-format will sort after system headers
#include "txm/base/image/fastjpeg/kernels/color_convert.h"

// BAD - may be sorted with system headers
#include <txm/base/image/fastjpeg/kernels/color_convert.h>
```

## 15. Visualization/UI Code
In visualization or UI code, don't strictly validate business data. Log errors and return/continue instead of crashing:
```cpp
// GOOD - in visualization code
if (!IsValid(data)) {
  LOG(ERROR) << "Invalid data received";
  return;
}

// BAD - in visualization code
CHECK(IsValid(data)) << "Data must be valid";
```

## 16. Timestamp and ID Handling
Don't compare timestamps for equality. Use message IDs or shared_ptr comparison for message consumption tracking:
```cpp
// BAD
if (current_msg.timestamp() == last_processed_timestamp_) {
  return;  // Already processed
}

// GOOD
if (current_msg_ptr_ == last_processed_msg_ptr_) {
  return;  // Already processed
}
```

## 17. Namespaces [GSG#Namespaces]
- **Never use `using namespace xxx`** - causes namespace pollution
- Use unnamed namespaces in `.cc` files for internal linkage (preferred over `static`) [GSG#Internal_Linkage] [TXM]
- Prefer relative namespace paths over fully qualified names when within a shared parent namespace [TXM]

```cpp
// BAD: Redundant root 'txm::base'
namespace txm::base::path {
void Function(txm::base::module::Widget w) { ... }
}

// GOOD: Clean relative path
namespace txm::base::path {
void Function(module::Widget w) { ... }
} // namespace txm::base::path
```

## 18. Variables [GSG#Local_Variables] [GSG#Static_and_Global_Variables]
- **Declare variables at first use**, not at function start - minimizes scope
- **Always initialize variables** at declaration
- **Avoid non-trivial static/global variables** - initialization order is undefined across translation units
- For global constants, prefer `constexpr` over `const` static variables
- **Avoid static local variables with dynamic initialization** in functions that may be called from multiple threads

## 19. Other C++ Features [GSG#Other_C++_Features]

### Exceptions [GSG#Exceptions]
- **Do not use C++ exceptions** - use `absl::Status` for error handling instead
- **Exception**: when integrating with third-party libraries that use exceptions, handle them at the boundary

### Type Casting [GSG#Casting]
- **Use C++ style casts**: `static_cast<>`, `const_cast<>`, `reinterpret_cast<>`
- **Use brace initialization** for arithmetic conversions: `int64_t{1} << 42`
- **Never use C-style casts**: `(int)x` → use `static_cast<int>(x)`
- **Avoid `dynamic_cast`**: prefer virtual functions for polymorphic behavior [GSG#Run-Time_Type_Information__RTTI_]

### Literals and Operators
- **Pointers**: use `nullptr`, not `0` or `NULL` [GSG#0_and_nullptr/NULL]
- **Integers**: use `0` for integer zero
- **Prefer `++i`** over `i++` (avoids unnecessary copy for iterators) [GSG#Preincrement_and_Predecrement]
- **Prefer `sizeof(var)`** over `sizeof(Type)` - stays correct if type changes [GSG#sizeof]

### Use of const [GSG#Use_of_const]
- **Use `const` wherever meaningful** - documents intent and enables compiler checks
- **`const` member functions**: mark if method doesn't modify object state
- **`const` local variables**: mark if not modified after initialization
- **`mutable`**: only for non-observable internal state (e.g., caches, mutexes)

### Integer Types [GSG#Integer_Types]
- **Use `int`** for general integers; use `int16_t`, `int32_t`, `int64_t` from `<cstdint>` when specific size needed
- **Avoid `short`, `long`, `long long`** - sizes vary across platforms
- **Avoid `unsigned` for non-negative values** - use signed types; unsigned only for bit operations/hashing

### Preprocessor Macros [GSG#Preprocessor_Macros]
- **Prefer modern C++ over macros**: use `constexpr` for constants, `inline` functions for code, `enum` for sets
- **Macro naming**: `ALL_CAPS_WITH_UNDERSCORES`
- **Header-exported macros**: must use project prefix (e.g., `TXM_CHECK_OK`) for global uniqueness
- **Multi-statement macros**: wrap in `do { ... } while (0)`

## 20. Designated Initializers [GSG#Designated_initializers]
- **Use designated initializers** for struct initialization - improves readability
- **Order must match definition** - initializers must appear in the same order as fields in struct definition

```cpp
struct Point { float x; float y; float z; };

// GOOD: Order matches definition
Point p = {.x = 1.0, .y = 2.0};  // z defaults to 0

// BAD: Wrong order - compilation error in C++20
Point p = {.y = 2.0, .x = 1.0};
```

## 21. Lambda Expressions [GSG#Lambda_expressions]
- **Keep lambdas short** - for complex logic, prefer named functions
- **Avoid default captures** (`[=]`, `[&]`) - explicitly list captured variables
- **Avoid capturing `this`** unless necessary - leads to lifetime issues
- **Use explicit parameter types** in function signatures that accept lambdas

```cpp
// GOOD: Short lambda, explicit capture
auto result = std::find_if(v.begin(), v.end(), [threshold](int x) { return x > threshold; });

// BAD: Long lambda with complex logic - use named function instead
auto process = [&](const Data& d) {
  // 20+ lines of complex processing...
};
```

## 22. Type Aliases [GSG#Aliases]
- **Prefer `using` over `typedef`** - clearer syntax, supports templates

```cpp
// GOOD: using alias
using IntVec = std::vector<int>;
template<typename T> using Vec = std::vector<T>;

// BAD: typedef (legacy style)
typedef std::vector<int> IntVec;
```

## 23. Switch Statements [GSG#Switch_Statements]
- **Always include `default` case** (unless switching on enum - compiler warns for unhandled values)
- **Use `[[fallthrough]]`** to annotate intentional fall-through between cases

```cpp
switch (x) {
  case 1:
    DoA();
    [[fallthrough]];  // Intentional fall-through
  case 2:
    DoB();
    break;
  default:
    LOG(FATAL) << "Unexpected value: " << x;
}
```

## 24. Formatting [GSG#Formatting]
- **Floating-point literals**: always include digits on both sides of decimal point (`1.0f` not `1.f` or `.5f`)
- **Return values**: don't wrap return expressions in unnecessary parentheses (`return x + y;` not `return (x + y);`)

## 25. Non-owning Views

### std::string_view
- **Prefer `std::string_view`** over `const std::string&` for read-only string parameters
- Accepts `const char*`, `std::string`, string literals - all without copying
- **Never store** `string_view` in class members (lifetime issue) - use `std::string` instead
- **Not null-terminated** - don't pass `.data()` to C APIs expecting null-terminated strings

### std::span
- **Prefer `std::span<const T>`** over `const std::vector<T>&` for read-only array parameters
- **Prefer `std::span<T>`** over `T* ptr, size_t len` for mutable array parameters
- Accepts `std::vector`, `std::array`, C arrays - all without copying
- **Never store** `span` in class members (lifetime issue)

